v1.30.5 - SECURITY: refresh-token family revocation on reuse (S-4, S-26)

The pre-patch /refresh rotation revoked the OLD token, but the LIVE
sibling issued during that rotation kept working. An attacker with a
phished refresh cookie could race the legitimate client: present R1
first, get R2 back, ride the session. The user's next /refresh would
401 ("token revoked"); they'd assume their session expired and
re-login, leaving the attacker holding the only live token in the
chain. There was no reuse detection -- a second presentation of an
already-rotated token never signalled theft.

Fix:
- Schema: new RefreshToken.familyId (String, indexed). On first issue
  (login / register / 2FA-login) familyId = self.id. On rotation the
  new token inherits the presented token's familyId.
- Migration 20260527120000_refresh_token_family is additive: ADD COLUMN
  nullable -> backfill familyId = id for every existing row -> SET NOT
  NULL -> CREATE INDEX. Existing tokens become self-rooted families;
  rotation chains can't be reconstructed retroactively but the
  reuse-detection logic only fires on already-revoked tokens, so the
  backfill never wrongly kills a session.
- authService.issueSession pre-generates the row id so familyId = id
  can self-root in one INSERT. Accepts optional { familyId } from
  refresh() to inherit the chain.
- authService.refresh detects reuse: when the presented token is found
  AND revokedAt is set, someone is replaying a token already rotated
  away. updateMany every sibling with that familyId where revokedAt
  IS NULL, set revokedAt = now. Attacker AND victim both die;
  legitimate user re-logs-in (correct response to detected theft).
- Unknown / expired / bad-signature tokens keep their boring 401 with
  no side effect. Those happen routinely and aren't theft signals.
- logout unchanged - deliberate single-token revoke, not a family kill.

3 new tests in describe('S-4 refresh-token family revocation'):
- Happy path: three consecutive /refresh calls succeed; DB read shows
  exactly one familyId for the user.
- Reuse cascade: rotate R1 -> R2, replay R1 -> R1 returns 401 AND R2
  is now also revoked (its next /refresh returns 401). Every row in
  the family has revokedAt set.
- Family isolation: two separate logins for the same user create two
  distinct families; reuse-revoking family A leaves family B fully
  working.

scim.test.ts seeded a RefreshToken directly without familyId; updated
to mirror the issueSession convention.

Verified: tsc clean. auth.test.ts 18/18. Full suite 290 passed,
5 skipped (LDAP).